g.text: One neat thing about the residual stream in transformers is that it can store information in independent (orthogonal) subspaces.
For instance, at the very start of our model we add together the token and positional embeddings.
If the token embeddings all lie in the , and the positional embeddings lie in the , then the model can preserve both pieces of information if the subspaces are orthogonal (or close to orthogonal).

A helpful image to have in mind is directions in low-dimensional space. If they're at right angles then we can recover each direction by projecting in that direction. But if they're not at right angles, we can't recover the signals faithfully.
You can extend this idea to much larger -dimensional spaces. The residual stream in GPT-3 has 768 dimensions, but it's still possible to read to and write from orthogonal subspaces.
In fact, because many of our matrices are much lower rank than their size (e.g. W = W W has size 768x768, but rank no greater than rank(W ) = 64) this is very often what ends up happening.
Different vector spaces come to represent different kinds of information in our model. I will represent this idea by explicitly writing vectors in terms of their value in each of these subspaces.

The query contains the information "I am A".
The key contains the information "I am B, and I follow A".
The query "I am A" searches for a key containing "I follow A".
It locates this key, extracts the information "I am B" from it, and
stores this information as "The next token will be B."
So the query now contains the information "The next token will be B."
The query contains the information "I am at posn #1."
The key contains the information "I am A, at posn #0."
The query "I am #1" searches for a key containing "I am #0".
It locates this key, extracts the information "I am A" from
it, and stores this information as "I follow A".
So the query now also contains the information "I follow A".
